Exercise 3: Principle Components Analysis

Our goal is to give you some conceptual basis to understand what is happening in a Principle components analysis to help guide you in interpretation. In addition to this weeks lecture and the reading material you may find this video helpful:

Open a new GENAVi window and load your data and metadata files via the Gene Expression and Differential Expression Analysis tabs as you did in the previous labs. Note you may need to run this command from a separate instance of R in a terminal so that you can continue to interact with this notebook:

shiny::runGitHub("alpreyes/GENAVi")

To run PCA or any of the functions from the Visualization tab you need to select some genes. Under the Gene selection menu you could select Select 1000 genes of highest variance but we will ignore that for now.

  1. Create a gene list of your differentially expressed genes from Lab 2. There are many ways to do this; here is an example for the dea object we created in the exercise above:
sig_genes <- with(dea, log2FoldChange - lfcSE > 0.5)
write.table(
  dea[sig_genes, ]$Symbol, 
  file = file.path(course_directory, "data", "tead_sig_genes.csv"),
  row.names = FALSE,
  col.names = FALSE,
  quote = FALSE)

On the Gene Expression tab upload your genelist via the Gene selection menu. Now click on the Visualization tab. It may take a minute to render. Once the heatmap is generated, click on the PCA plots button. Choose Selected genes from the PCA Genes menus. Download a copy of the image and link it below.

Now go back to the gene expression tab and select Deselect all genes from the Gene selection menu. Then search for your target gene (or any gene of interest). Select some number of genes (at least 3). Return to the Visualization tab and make sure PCA genes >> Selected genes is selected. Link your image here:
